        "identifier": "ID",
        "info": "The French R is produced at the back of the throat using the uvula, rather than with the tongue tip like the Spanish R. Air is pushed through a narrow space near the uvula, creating a gentle vibration or “gargling” sound. There are two possible realizations of this sound: the fricative and the trill. In the fricative (/ʁ/), air flows continuously through the narrow gap, producing a smooth, steady, and slightly resonant sound. In the trill (/ʀ/), the uvula flaps rapidly in the airflow, creating a series of discrete pulses and a bouncier quality. Most French speakers use the fricative in everyday speech, while the trill is less common and mostly optional.",
        "native_language": "english",
        "learning_language": "french",
        "native_group": "1 alphabet",
